		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+16" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF"><B>The UK Today</B></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="_sans" SIZE="12" COLOR="#000000"> </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000">Today saw the launch of the new daily newspaper 'The UK Today'. According to the paper's editor, Charles Moody, 'The UK Today' is aimed at a younger twenty-something <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[1]</FONT> and is expected to reach an average <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[2]</FONT> of 200,000 in its first year. </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="_sans" SIZE="12" COLOR="#000000"> </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000">Although the paper is <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[3]</FONT> in format, Moody was quick to point out that it will have as much serious news as any of the <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[4]</FONT>. One of its most striking features is its highly unusual <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[5]</FONT>. Articles aren't laid out in <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[6]</FONT> but in boxes, each accompanied by a colour photograph. </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="_sans" SIZE="12" COLOR="#000000"> </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000">You'll find all the usual sections - national and international news, financial news, arts and entertainment, sport and, of course, <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[7] </FONT>advertisements. </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="_sans" SIZE="12" COLOR="#000000"> </FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000">So, what's in today's <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[8]</FONT>? Well, on the <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[9]</FONT>, under the eye-catching banner <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[10]</FONT> 'More hot air?' is an in-depth <FONT COLOR="#0000FF">[11]</FONT> on the outcomes of this week's international summit meeting on global warming. Well worth a read!</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
